Thanks for putting this together Tim. I have one big disagreement though, and that's about when to cut from one shot to the next. In general, when it comes to videos, especially rocket videos, the temptation to cut should be resisted more than it is. Less cutting and longer shots allow the viewer to get a better immersive sense of what's happening. To my mind, a longer single shot is more enjoyable but that's not what usually happens. Specifically, the shot from 6:35 should not have been switched at 6:41. That degraded the experience, at least for me. The shot from 6:35 should have gone, uninterrupted, all the way to contact with the ground at 6:44. It would have been much more enjoyable.

The first indicator that there is a problem is the dark plumes of smoke trailing flame exhaust. It's a sign that the engine is releasing carbon particles. The fuel in not burning cleanly or completely.

At the speed of descent, the Starship had fallen too far, going too fast, for restart to initiate and the vertical maneuver to stabilize nd the thruster to slow the descent to a safe landing speed.

The 1st engine restart is meant to begin stabilizing the Starships descent as it reorients itself. The 2nd engine restart is meant to decelerate starship, with engine 1 for landing. This is a failure.

To solve this problem, all 3 engine must restart. 2 are to stabilize the reorientation to vertical while the 3r engine begins deceleration. Then the other 2 engine join in the deceleration to landing. But all this must begin at a height above 2000 meters to overcome the pull of gravity

So......work on correcting the reorientation from horizontal to vertical at a higher altitudes.... Before working on the deceleration to landing problem.
**You can't fix every problem at once !!**!
